  "genres": ["Biography", "History"],  
  "review": "I am an avid reader of books about the Wild West. This one particularly appealed to me because of my personal connection to the Southwest and because it covered a period of time that I knew personally. My grandfather was a cavalryman in the Spanish American War and fought with General Crook against Geronimo. He was one of the lucky ones who survived the 1886 massacre at Apache Wells. That's why I watched this movie with special interest. I liked the way the film makers handled the opening scene of the movie. The camera was inside the wagon following the stagecoach. The sound of the horses hooves clattering on the pavement and the dust blowing around the horses added to the realism of the action. The scenes of the Native Americans riding bareback were convincing, especially the way they rode in unison. The scene of the attack on the bank robbers was exciting. One of the men was shot and killed by Doc's hat. I liked the scenes of the shootout in the OK corral. The actors were believable in their roles. The scene of the burial of Doc was beautiful. It captured the spirit of the era. I'm glad I rented it."  
}

